Lab 07 – Neuro Alliance: Collaborative Intelligence
Course: ITAI 4374 – Neuroscience as a Model for AI
Student: Orhan Gumus
Semester: Spring 2026

What I Did
This lab explored the concept of "Neuro Alliance" — the idea that brain-inspired systems and conventional AI can be combined to create more robust and capable intelligence. The work centered on how human cognitive strategies and AI computational strengths complement each other.
Key activities included:

Analyzing hybrid systems that combine biological and artificial processing strategies
Investigating ensemble methods and their parallels to multi-region brain cooperation
Exploring how different brain regions specialize and collaborate (e.g., hippocampus for memory, prefrontal cortex for planning)
Designing and testing a small collaborative model that leverages multiple specialized sub-networks


What I Learned
This lab brought together threads from the entire course into a unified framework. The idea that intelligence — whether biological or artificial — benefits from specialization and cooperation is a profound one. Just as the brain's regions don't operate in isolation, AI systems that combine specialized modules tend to outperform monolithic approaches on complex tasks.
I also gained a stronger appreciation for transfer learning as an AI analog to the brain's ability to apply prior knowledge to new domains quickly and with minimal additional experience.

Challenges I Faced

Coordinating information flow between specialized sub-networks required careful interface design.
Deciding which tasks to assign to which "module" was more art than science — it highlighted how much we still don't know about optimal cognitive division of labor.
Evaluating the combined system fairly against single-model baselines required thoughtful experimental design.
